---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Political stylometry — what parties do, say, and how they think"
  description="A data-driven analysis of the Swedish parliament 2022–2026, treating roll-call votes, reservations and speeches as behavioural data."
>
  <article class="container">
    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="byline">Sveriges riksdag 2022–2026 · A data-driven analysis</p>
      <h1>What parties do, say, and how they think</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Politics is usually described in slogans. This is an attempt to
        describe it in data. Two and a half thousand chamber votes, eleven
        thousand written dissents, and fifty thousand speeches — read as
        behaviour, not rhetoric.
      </p>
    </header>

    <p>
      In the parliamentary year 2022/23 the Sweden Democrats voted with the
      governing parties (Moderates, Christian Democrats, Liberals) on 67 % of
      chamber votes. By 2025/26, the election year, that figure was 98 %. In
      the same year the number of dissenting opinions ("reservationer") filed
      by SD collapsed from 749 to 17. The party that runs against the
      establishment had effectively merged with it on the record, one year
      before the election.
    </p>

    <p>
      That is one of several patterns that surface when you treat the
      Riksdag's open data as behavioural data — a way of reconstructing
      ideology, coalition structure and consensus from what actually happens
      in the chamber, not from what parties say in their own materials.
    </p>

    <p class="pullquote">
      SD is no longer just voting with the government — they have stopped
      filing their own alternative positions on the record.
    </p>

    <h2>Three questions a voter compass should ask</h2>
    <p>
      Two voters can give the same answer to "should we raise the carbon
      tax?" for opposite reasons. One because climate change is existential,
      the other because they distrust whoever would spend the revenue.
      Matched to the same party, at least one of them will be disappointed
      when that party governs.
    </p>
    <p>
      A more honest framing separates three questions a party can be asked,
      each of which can be answered differently:
    </p>
    <ol class="axis-list">
      <li class="axis-list--vad">
        <span class="axis-tag">WHAT</span>
        the party's actual position on the issue, measured by how its
        members have voted.
      </li>
      <li class="axis-list--varfor">
        <span class="axis-tag">WHY</span>
        the party's value framing, measured by how it justifies its
        positions in reservations and committee reports.
      </li>
      <li class="axis-list--hur">
        <span class="axis-tag">HOW</span>
        the party's preferred mechanisms: market or regulation, prevention
        or punishment, central or local, universal or targeted.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Sometimes these three point the same way. More often they don't — and
      that is precisely where a one-number "you are 87 % Centerpartist"
      compass becomes misleading.
    </p>

    <h2>Part 1 — What parties do</h2>
    <p>
      The Swedish parliament is one of the world's most extensively
      documented. Every chamber vote is published as open data, member by
      member. Across the 2022–2026 mandate that comes to 2,501 votes and
      872,849 individual roll-call entries. Project the matrix — 349 seats
      by ~2,500 votes — and let a standard algorithm look for hidden
      structure (PCA), and a non-random picture emerges.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/01_behavioural_map.png`} alt="Behavioural map of the Riksdag based on voting patterns, 2022–2026" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The Riksdag 2022–2026, projected into two dimensions via PCA on the
        voting matrix. The first axis (PC1, 46 % of variance) separates the
        Tidö government bloc from the opposition. The second (PC2, 13.5 %)
        splits the opposition into an S arm and a V/MP/C arm. Centerpartiet
        sits at the centre of the first axis but well down on the second:
        geographically centrist, behaviourally close to the soft left.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The pattern itself is familiar from American roll-call research but
      hasn't been visualised this directly for Swedish conditions. What is
      worth noting is what's <em>not</em> there: no "new political centre",
      no coalition cutting across blocs, no realignment from Centerpartiet.
      What there is, is two blocs — and a background structure in which V,
      MP and C sit tightly packed even though they officially represent
      different ideological traditions.
    </p>

    <h3>The Tidö bloc converged — but not in the direction most assumed</h3>
    <p>
      The most interesting movement in the mandate is invisible in the
      static map above. It only appears when the same analysis is run year
      by year.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/07_tido_collapse.png`} alt="The Tidö bloc collapsing into a single cluster, 2022/23 to 2025/26" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The four parties of the Tidö bloc (M, KD, L plus SD as a support
        party), per parliamentary year. The mean pairwise distance between
        their centroids falls from 9.08 (2022/23) to 0.43 (2025/26). By
        2025/26 the four points sit on top of one another.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The technical reading: the bloc's parties vote increasingly alike.
      The simpler reading — because the cabinet (M, KD, L) has always
      voted as a unit by definition — is that <em>SD has moved towards
      the cabinet's positions</em>, not the other way around. And the
      movement has accelerated.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/08_agreement_trend.png`} alt="Tidö bloc vote agreement over the mandate" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        <strong>Left panel</strong>: share of chamber votes where the
        entire Tidö bloc voted unanimously. The share rose from 73 % in
        2024/25 to 98 % in 2025/26, in step with the start of the
        election year.
        <strong>Right panel</strong>: the rise is entirely driven by SD
        aligning with the cabinet's positions.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      67 % → 98 % can sound dry. What it actually means: in the 687
      chamber votes of the election year, SD deviated from the government
      in 11 of them. In the same year SD's own dissenting opinions fell
      from 574 (2024/25) to 17 (2025/26), while the four opposition
      parties' reservations rose by 40–70 %.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/21_sd_reservation_collapse.png`} alt="SD reservations by parliamentary year — the election-year collapse" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Reservations filed per party and parliamentary year. The thick
        yellow line is SD: 749 → 402 → 574 → 17. The opposition parties
        rise or hold steady. The cabinet parties (M, KD, L) are excluded
        — as the majority, they hardly file any.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      It is one of several figures that probably should not have to be
      published one year before an election.
    </p>

    <h2>Part 2 — What parties say</h2>
    <p>
      Votes are one thing. Text is another. Together with 10,931
      reservations (2.8 million words in total) and 54,914 chamber
      speeches, the Riksdag's record gives us both action and
      justification. We used a Swedish language model —
      <a href="https://huggingface.co/KBLab/sentence-bert-swedish-cased">KBLab/sentence-bert-swedish-cased</a>
      from the National Library — to translate these texts into
      comparable vectors.
    </p>

    <p>
      The natural question becomes: when two parties vote alike, do they
      also speak alike? And conversely, when they vote differently, can
      they still argue from the same values?
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/15_pair_what_vs_why.png`} alt="Party pairs — vote agreement vs reasoning agreement" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Each point is a pair of parties. X axis: how similarly they vote;
        Y axis: how similarly they reason (cosine distance between
        topic-centred text vectors). The trend line is the expected
        relationship. Pairs above the line argue more alike than they
        vote; pairs below vote together but argue differently.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h3>Three patterns worth noting</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>S and C vote together 91 % of the time — but argue
      separately.</strong> This is not a values-based alliance. They are
      two parties that happen to end up on the same side opposing the
      government, but don't speak the same language in their reservations.
      A voter who likes C's reasoning but votes-matches S should know
      that.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>M and SD vote alike (83 %) and argue alike.</strong> This
      is the only party pair above the trend line with positive reasoning
      similarity. The explanation isn't that M says what SD says about
      what they vote for — it's that M's textual register has moved
      towards SD's. A weaker convergence than the SD-towards-government
      one, but in the opposite direction.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>V and MP are a genuine left bloc.</strong> They vote
      together 93 % of the time and they argue from the same values. The
      left-leaning voter hesitating between them isn't choosing between
      different ideologies but between two variants of the same one.
    </p>

    <h2>Part 3 — How parties propose</h2>
    <p>
      The third axis is the theory of change: <em>how</em> should society
      be changed? Market or regulation? Prevention or punishment? National
      or local? Universal or targeted welfare? These are not policy
      positions; they are preferences for mechanism.
    </p>

    <p>
      We combine two signals. One is which parties <em>co-sign</em>
      reservations — when two parties put their names on the same
      alternative proposal, they share a concrete theory of how it should
      be done. The other is a lexical analysis of their speech texts
      across the four dimensions above.
    </p>

    <p>
      The result produces more surprises than the first two axes. The
      Sweden Democrats have zero co-signed reservations with any other
      party — not even with KD, with whom they vote identically.
      Centerpartiet files 910 entirely solo reservations, more than any
      other party. And Socialdemokraterna and Kristdemokraterna land
      with strikingly high "how" similarity — despite being on opposite
      blocs. Both are "established administrative parties". They speak
      with the same vocabulary about how the state should manage its
      tasks, even when they disagree on what those tasks should be.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/16_three_axis.png`} alt="WHAT × WHY × HOW — party pairs across three axes" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Summary of the three axes. Each line is a party pair. Green:
        consistent across all three axes (cabinet trio, V–MP). Orange:
        high disagreement between axes (S–L, M–SD, S–C — pairs where
        "what" and "why" don't say the same thing). Purple: opposed on
        all three (V–L).
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <hr />

    <p style="font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-muted);">
      All analysis is based on reproducible methods over public data
      from <a href="https://data.riksdagen.se">data.riksdagen.se</a>.
      Source code and full method writeup at
      <a href="https://github.com/freol35241/ps-sverige">GitHub</a>.
      No party interviews, no surveys, no subjective judgments beyond
      those required to classify topics and word choices — and those
      are openly documented in the code.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
